      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at houses in austin and im kinda confused about the earnest money thing. like why do i have to put that in an escrow account instead of just giving it to the seller? feels weird to have it just sitting there.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Earnest money, a good-faith deposit, is not just a random pile of cash, it's a crucial piece of the deal, and you need to keep it safe! It's placed in escrow because, frankly, you never know what a tricky situation might pop up, like a botched appraisal or a sudden need for a new inspection. If you just handed it to the seller, and things went sideways—say, the seller decides they don't want to close for some reason—you'd be stuck, right? Holding it in escrow is like putting your valuable coin in a locked, secure chest guarded by a neutral party. This neutral party, the escrow agent, is there to make sure both sides stick to the rules.",
